{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487334"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"322"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/322"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.55,0.07,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/322"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42058"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a lesion on the right side of his nose. This has been present for about seven years and he has recently noticed that it appears to be increasing in size (Image). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cryotherapy","Referral for excision","5-fluorouracil cream","Review in 12 months","Imiquimod cream"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis photograph most likely shows a lentigo maligna, which is melanoma in situ. These lesions occur in sun-damaged areas, most commonly on the face. Due to the risk of growth/transformation into melanoma (5% risk) they should be removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor facial pigmented lesions suspicious of melanoma or lentigo maligna excisional biopsy with 2mm margins is recommended where possible. This reduces sampling area associated with partial biopsies (e.g. punch or shave biopsies), which can result when biopsying lesions of heterogenous histological appearance, and result in missing cases of melanoma. This is important as 20-60% of melanomas can have associated components of melanocytic naevus. To put it in context, the false-negative diagnosis rates for punch, shave and excisional biopsies for pigmented lesions has been demonstrated to be 23.3%, 4.5% and\u00a01.7%, respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, it is worth while noting that complete excision of facial lesions may not always be possible or practical due to large size, difficult location or being present in cosmetically sensitive areas. In these cases partial biopsy via shave or punch may be more appropriate, or referral to a dermatologist for biopsies and further management - the decision will depend on both patient factors (size and location of the lesion) and clinician factors (such as their experience, training and confidence in dermatological excisions). Of the options provided \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for excision \u003C/strong\u003Eis therefore the most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for suspected melanocytic lesions as it destroys the tissue without providing a specimen for histological examination, which is essential for diagnosis and determining the need for further treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical creams (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003E5-fluorouracil cream\u003C/strong\u003E) could be used for basal cell carcinomas, but not for melanotic lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt would be inappropriate to send this patient away and\u003Cstrong\u003E review in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E as there is risk of malignant transformation to melanoma, which can be aggressive and spread quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eimiquimod cream\u003C/strong\u003E has been used in some cases of lentigo maligna when patients are not surgical candidates, surgery remains the standard and preferred treatment due to its higher cure rate and the ability to histologically assess the entire lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any recent change to a lentigo maligna should be followed by excision and histological assessment.","Lentigo maligna is melanoma in situ that occurs in sun-damaged areas, most commonly on the face.","Surgical excision is the standard treatment for lentigo maligna due to the 5% risk of transformation into invasive melanoma."],"references":["Oakley A.\u00a0Lentigo maligna and lentigo maligna melanoma. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2011. Available at:\u00a0https://dermnetnz.org/topics/lentigo-maligna-and-lentigo-maligna-melanoma/","Sladden MJ, Nieweg OE, Julie Howle J, et al. Updated evidence-based clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of melanoma: definitive excision margins for primary cutaneous melanoma. Med J Aust 2018; 208:137-42.","Ungureanu L, Vasilovici AF, Trufin II, et al. Lentigo Maligna Treatment\u2014An Update. J. Clin. Med. 2024, 13, 2527","Adybeik D, Ciranni D, Alaei L. Punch biopsy is best avoided for clinically suspicious pigmented lesions. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:354-6. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/punch-biopsy-is-best-avoided-for-clinically-suspic"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"322"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14418"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14418"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/24d8cb5f-b740-4030-8f60-cfa421dfb6bc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/24d8cb5f-b740-4030-8f60-cfa421dfb6bc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T08:25:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T08:25:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"322"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108932"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}